Name: Closed fireplace Wood and Pellet Combustion
Sampling Method: Sampling within the chimney (over a bbq) with an aluminium 'frame' to facilitate cooling (40C). On this frame Piteau pipes were inserted and the exhaust was pumped trough transparens silicon pipes by a pneumatic circuit connected with a low-volume pump. Measurement were made with a flow of 20  5 l/min and an exposition time of 10-20 minutes.

Measurement were made with a flow of 20  5 l/min and an exposition time of 10-20 minutes.

Name: Fertilizer production
Analythical Method: ICP-MS, inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry
Sampling Method: Filters collected at the the impact point of emission plume on the ground in the proximities of emission sources with Graseby Andersen reference high volume captors (EN12341, 68 m3/h). The impact points were detected with the support of a correlation spectrometer (COSPEC) and a real time SO2 analyzer at the ground. Due to the episode duration the captors sampled a low volume of air, giving rise to some artifacts (see text). The relative analytical errors are declared to be between 3% and 10% for all elements studied.

Sampling Method: Filters collected at the the impact point of emission plume on the ground in the proximities of emission sources with Graseby Andersen reference high volume captors (EN12341, 68 m3/h). The impact points were detected with the support of a correlation spectrometer (COSPEC) and a real time SO2 analyzer at the ground. Due to the episode duration the captors sampled a low volume of air, giving rise to some artifacts (see text). The relative analytical errors are declared to be between 3% and 10% for all elements studied.

The impact points were detected with the support of a correlation spectrometer (COSPEC) and a real time SO2 analyzer at the ground. Due to the episode duration the captors sampled a low volume of air, giving rise to some artifacts (see text). The relative analytical errors are declared to be between 3% and 10% for all elements studied.

Sampling Method: Filters collected at the the impact point of emission plume on the ground in the proximities of emission sources with Graseby Andersen reference high volume captors (EN12341, 68 m3/h). The impact points were detected with the support of a correlation spectrometer (COSPEC) and a real time SO2 analyzer at the ground. Due to the episode duration the captors sampled a low volume of air, giving rise to some artifacts (see text). The relative analytical errors are declared to be between 3% and 10% for all elements studied.

Name: Ship exhaust
Analythical Method: EGA Evolved Gas Analyses by thermaloptical analyzer (OC/EC)
Place: Celtic Sea, the English Channel and the North Sea
Sampling Method: The analysed exhaust from the 20.2 MW (84% load) main engine was sampled through three holes in the exhaust pipe positioned ca. 25 m behind the engine and 40 m before the funnel exit plane. Properties of the particulate matter were investigated in the hot-exhaust gas sampled in a diluted and cooled gas sampled in the dilution system.  (PM, OC and Sulphate) or on average with hot exhaust (only for EC and Ash). Ash data not inserted in the Db.

Name: Pellets type I
Analythical Method: ICP-OES (AES), Inductively Coupled Plasma Optical (Atomic) Emission Spectrometer
Sampling Method: PM10 was collected after the dilution of the exhaust with atmospheric air in a tunnel under isokinetic condition. A cascade impactor TCR Tecora (model MSSI) with multistage cascade impactor, designed according to ISO23210-2009. Top-feed pellet stove with a nominal output of 9.5 kW Solzaima, model Alpes.  The ignition phase was not included in the results.
